I would read the node as string and write it as a string. That&#39;s the only sure way. 

```
// Setting the default settings is the only way I know to affect settings
// for DeserializeXmlNode, there may be a better way
Newtonsoft.Json.JsonConvert.DefaultSettings = 
    () =&gt; new Newtonsoft.Json.JsonSerializerSettings() { 
    DateParseHandling = Newtonsoft.Json.DateParseHandling.None };
```
# Test

```
var json = @&quot;
{
    &quot;&quot;Flight&quot;&quot;: {
        &quot;&quot;FlightNumber&quot;&quot;: &quot;&quot;747&quot;&quot;,
        &quot;&quot;Source&quot;&quot;: &quot;&quot;JFK&quot;&quot;,
        &quot;&quot;Destination&quot;&quot;: &quot;&quot;LAS&quot;&quot;,   
        &quot;&quot;Status&quot;&quot;: &quot;&quot;ON TIME&quot;&quot;,
        &quot;&quot;DepDateTime&quot;&quot;: &quot;&quot;2019-10-25T07:00:00-05:00&quot;&quot;,
        &quot;&quot;Terminal&quot;&quot;: &quot;&quot;2&quot;&quot;
    }
}            
&quot;;

Newtonsoft.Json.JsonConvert.DefaultSettings = () =&gt; new Newtonsoft.Json.JsonSerializerSettings() { DateParseHandling = Newtonsoft.Json.DateParseHandling.None };

System.Xml.XmlDocument xmlDoc = Newtonsoft.Json.JsonConvert.DeserializeXmlNode(json);
Console.WriteLine(xmlDoc.InnerXml);
```

# Output

```
(...)&lt;DepDateTime&gt;2019-10-25T07:00:00-05:00&lt;/DepDateTime&gt;&lt;Terminal&gt;2&lt;/Terminal&gt;&lt;/Flight&gt;
```

## Output without setting the settings

```
(...)&lt;DepDateTime&gt;2019-10-25T22:00:00+10:00&lt;/DepDateTime&gt;&lt;Terminal&gt;2&lt;/Terminal&gt;&lt;/Flight&gt;
```

Your problem is that Json.NET&#39;s [automatic `DateTime` recognition](https://www.newtonsoft.com/json/help/html/DatesInJSON.htm) recognizes that the string `&quot;2019-10-25T07:00:00-05:00&quot;` is a valid [ISO 8601](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601) date and time and parses it to a [`DateTime`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.datetime?view=netframework-4.8) -- which unfortunately does not have support for timezone specification.  Thus the value gets converted (correctly) to the local timezone on your computer during deserialization and subsequently formatted as such in the XML.

To prevent this, you need to parse the JSON using [`DateParseHandling.None` or `DateParseHandling.DateTimeOffset`](https://www.newtonsoft.com/json/help/html/T_Newtonsoft_Json_DateParseHandling.htm), however [`JsonConvert.DeserializeXmlNode`](https://www.newtonsoft.com/json/help/html/Overload_Newtonsoft_Json_JsonConvert_DeserializeXmlNode.htm) has no overload that allows this setting to be passed in.  Thus you will need to create an extension method with the necessary argument:

	public static partial class JsonExtensions
	{
		public static XmlDocument DeserializeXmlNode(string json, DateParseHandling dateParseHandling, 
													 string deserializeRootElementName = null, bool writeArrayAttribute = false, bool encodeSpecialCharacters = false)
		{
			var settings = new JsonSerializerSettings
			{
				Converters = 
				{ 
					new Newtonsoft.Json.Converters.XmlNodeConverter() 
					{
						DeserializeRootElementName = deserializeRootElementName,
						WriteArrayAttribute = writeArrayAttribute,
						EncodeSpecialCharacters = encodeSpecialCharacters
					} 
				},
				DateParseHandling = dateParseHandling,
			};

    		return JsonConvert.DeserializeObject&lt;XmlDocument&gt;(json, settings);
		}
	}

Then use it as follows:

    var xmlDoc = JsonExtensions.DeserializeXmlNode(jsonString, DateParseHandling.None);

Note that both `DateParseHandling.None` and `DateParseHandling.DateTimeOffset` meet your needs, as the former disables ISO 8601 date recognition while the latter parses such strings into [`DateTimeOffset`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.datetimeoffset?view=netframework-4.8) which does support time zone specification.

Incidentally, the equivalent method for those who prefer the newer [`XDocument`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.xml.linq.xdocument?view=netframework-4.8) is:

	public static partial class JsonExtensions
	{
		public static XDocument DeserializeXNode(string json, DateParseHandling dateParseHandling, 
													 string deserializeRootElementName = null, bool writeArrayAttribute = false, bool encodeSpecialCharacters = false)
		{
			var settings = new JsonSerializerSettings
			{
				Converters = 
				{ 
					new Newtonsoft.Json.Converters.XmlNodeConverter() 
					{
						DeserializeRootElementName = deserializeRootElementName,
						WriteArrayAttribute = writeArrayAttribute,
						EncodeSpecialCharacters = encodeSpecialCharacters
					} 
				},
				DateParseHandling = dateParseHandling,
			};

    		return JsonConvert.DeserializeObject&lt;XDocument&gt;(json, settings);
		}
	}

Demo fiddle [here](https://dotnetfiddle.net/YouG3Z).

